{{Orphan|date=January 2018}}
{{Infobox sport | name = GeoSpy | image = | imagesize = | caption = | union = | nickname = | first = December 11, 2013<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geospy.org/register/objects |title=www.geospy.org |publisher=www.geospy.org |date= |accessdate=20 June 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202145515/http://www.geospy.org/register/objects|archivedate=February 2, 2014}}</ref> | registered = | clubs = | contact = | team = Optional | mgender = | category = Outdoor Recreation Activity | equipment = [[GPS navigation device|GPS receiver]] or GPS-enabled mobile device, Camera | venue = Worldwide | obsolete = | olympic = }}
'''GeoSpy''' is an outdoor recreational activity which combines geographic locations and maps with [[photography]] in a location-based game. To play the game requires a camera and a mobile [[Global Positioning System]] (GPS) device.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planettechnews.com/online/geospy-org-a-new-outdoor-game-for-photographers-and-travelers |title=www.planettechnews.com |publisher=[[PlanetTech]] |date= |accessdate=20 June 2014}}</ref>
There are several goals in the game, but the primary one is to find and create objects through pictures of objects and places which are uploaded to the game's website.
To create an object the participant requires a complete knowledge about the object, and the GPS coordinates and photos of the object that the participant has taken. Similarly, existing objects can be secured by visiting and photographing the object and posting the photo on the game’s website as proof that the competitor visited the object. The objects are divided into different categories namely Civil, Religious & Historical, Natural, Technical and Military objects with further sub-categories such as hospitals, museums, factories, memorials, etc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.techgreet.com/geospy-an-interactive-browser-game/ |title=TechGreet.com |publisher=www.techgreet.com |date= |accessdate=20 June 2014}}</ref>
Participants in the game are called spies.
